  <article class="container max-w-4xl py-10">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Investment Property Mortgage Renewal in Canada: The Complete Landlord's Guide</h1>
    <p class="text-lg mb-8" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Updated March 2026 · 8-minute read</p>

    <p class="mb-6 text-base leading-relaxed">Renewing a rental or investment property mortgage in Canada involves different rules, higher rates, and unique qualifying criteria compared to owner-occupied properties. Whether you own a single rental condo or a growing portfolio of multi-unit residential properties, understanding how lenders treat investment properties at renewal is essential to maximizing your returns and accessing the best financing.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Investment Property Rate Premium</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The most immediate difference you'll notice when renewing an investment property mortgage: rates are higher than for owner-occupied properties. The premium is typically 0.10%–0.50% above comparable owner-occupied rates, reflecting the higher perceived risk of investment properties (historically, landlords are statistically more likely to strategically default than owner-occupants in financial distress).</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The exact premium varies by:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2 leading-relaxed">
      <li><strong>Lender type:</strong> Some monolines and credit unions are more competitive on rental property rates than major banks. A broker can identify which lenders are most aggressive in the investment property space at the time of your renewal.</li>
      <li><strong>LTV:</strong> Lower LTV (more equity) typically reduces the rate premium. A rental property at 50% LTV may get better pricing than one at 75% LTV.</li>
      <li><strong>Property type:</strong> A single-family rental house typically qualifies for the lowest rates. Multi-unit residential (2–4 units) has a slightly higher premium. Commercial residential (5+ units) moves to a different, typically higher-rate product.</li>
      <li><strong>Portfolio size:</strong> Landlords with multiple properties may face additional scrutiny from lenders regarding overall exposure.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Rental Income Qualifying</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Rental income is counted in mortgage qualification, but not at full face value. Different lenders have different approaches to what percentage of gross rental income they'll use when calculating your debt service ratios.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background: var(--primary); color: white">
            <th class="p-3 text-left">Approach</th>
            <th class="p-3 text-left">How It Works</th>
            <th class="p-3 text-left">Typical Qualifying Income %</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border)">
            <td class="p-3 font-medium">Offset Method</td>
            <td class="p-3">Rental income is used to offset the rental property's expenses in the TDS calculation. The net (rental income minus expenses) either adds to or reduces your qualifying income.</td>
            <td class="p-3">50–80% of gross rent, depending on lender</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b" style="border-color: var(--border); background: var(--muted)">
            <td class="p-3 font-medium">Add-Back Method</td>
            <td class="p-3">Full rental income is added to employment income. All property expenses (mortgage, tax, insurance) appear in the TDS as debts. Less favorable for most borrowers.</td>
            <td class="p-3">Up to 100% of gross rent added; full expenses counted</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-color: var(--border)">
            <td class="p-3 font-medium">DSCR Method</td>
            <td class="p-3">Debt Service Coverage Ratio approach: rental income must cover a certain multiple of the mortgage payment. Used by some specialized rental mortgage programs — less reliant on personal income.</td>
            <td class="p-3">Rental income must be 1.0–1.25x or higher than mortgage payment</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Most A-lenders use a rental offset approach with 50–80% of gross rental income. The specific percentage matters significantly — a lender that counts 80% of your rent versus one counting 50% can mean the difference between qualifying or not qualifying for the full mortgage amount.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">No Stress Test on Straight Switch — Post-2024</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The November 2024 rule change eliminating the stress test for straight lender switches at renewal applies to investment properties as well as owner-occupied homes — provided the switch is a true straight transfer (same balance, same amortization, no new funds).</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">This is significant for investment property owners. Prior to this change, many landlords found themselves locked into their existing lender because switching required a full stress test on the rental income qualifying, which many couldn't pass when combined with their other property obligations. The new straight-switch rule removes this barrier for most rental property renewals.</p>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">The practical implication: even if your income situation hasn't improved since you first got the mortgage, you may now be able to switch to a lender offering better rental property rates — simply by keeping the same balance and amortization. A broker can run this analysis for you.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Multi-Unit Properties: When Commercial Rules Apply</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">There's an important threshold in Canadian mortgage lending: residential rules (which this guide primarily covers) apply to properties with 1–4 units. Properties with 5 or more units are classified as commercial real estate for mortgage purposes, with fundamentally different rules:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2 leading-relaxed">
      <li><strong>Commercial underwriting:</strong> Qualification is based primarily on the property's income performance (NOI — Net Operating Income) rather than personal income and debt ratios.</li>
      <li><strong>Higher rates:</strong> Commercial mortgage rates are typically higher than residential investment property rates, often 0.50%–1.50% above comparable residential products.</li>
      <li><strong>Shorter amortization:</strong> Commercial mortgages often have amortization of 20–25 years maximum, with terms commonly 5–10 years.</li>
      <li><strong>CMHC MLI Select:</strong> CMHC's Multi-Unit Mortgage Loan Insurance program provides insurance for 5+ unit properties and has been expanded in recent years, enabling lower rates and longer amortizations (up to 50 years in some cases) for purpose-built rental projects meeting certain criteria.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Portfolio Landlords: Beyond 3–5 Properties</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Most major banks and many monolines cap the number of properties or total mortgage amount they'll lend to a single borrower for rental properties. Typically:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2 leading-relaxed">
      <li><strong>Major banks:</strong> Often cap at 4–6 rental properties or a maximum total exposure of $2–5 million across all rental mortgages before requiring additional conditions or declining.</li>
      <li><strong>Monolines:</strong> Some monolines (particularly First National's Excalibur program and similar) are specifically designed for portfolio landlords with higher thresholds — some lending to landlords with 10+ properties.</li>
      <li><strong>Alternative approach:</strong> Portfolio landlords often use different lenders for different properties to avoid hitting any single lender's exposure limits. A broker coordinates this.</li>
      <li><strong>Commercial mortgage lenders:</strong> For large portfolios, dedicated commercial lenders may be more appropriate than residential lenders.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Cash Flow Analysis at Renewal</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Renewal is the right time to recalculate your investment property's cash flow position with your new rate — particularly important in 2025–2026 as many landlords who locked in at 2020–2021 rates are renewing at significantly higher rates.</p>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-5 mb-6" style="background: var(--accent); border-left: 4px solid var(--secondary)">
      <p class="font-bold mb-2">Simple Rental Cash Flow Calculation</p>
      <div class="text-sm space-y-1">
        <p>Monthly gross rent: <strong>$2,800</strong></p>
        <p>Less: Mortgage payment (new rate): <strong>–$1,850</strong></p>
        <p>Less: Property tax (monthly): <strong>–$280</strong></p>
        <p>Less: Insurance (monthly): <strong>–$120</strong></p>
        <p>Less: Property management (10%): <strong>–$280</strong></p>
        <p>Less: Vacancy / maintenance reserve (5%): <strong>–$140</strong></p>
        <p class="font-bold mt-2" style="color: var(--secondary)">Net monthly cash flow: +$130</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Example figures only. Your actual numbers will vary.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">If your cash flow has turned negative at the new renewal rate, consider:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-1 leading-relaxed">
      <li>Aggressively shopping for the lowest possible renewal rate (a broker is essential)</li>
      <li>Reviewing rent levels against market to ensure you're not below market</li>
      <li>Evaluating whether the property should be refinanced to improve terms (if LTV allows and income qualifies)</li>
      <li>In extreme cases, whether selling the property makes more financial sense than carrying negative cash flow</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Tax: Mortgage Interest Is Deductible on Rental Properties</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Unlike your primary residence (where mortgage interest is not deductible), the mortgage interest on a rental property is a legitimate tax deduction against your rental income. This means that the after-tax cost of your investment property mortgage is lower than the stated rate — the actual cost to you depends on your marginal tax rate.</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Example: If you're in a 45% marginal tax bracket and your rental property mortgage costs you $24,000/year in interest, the after-tax cost is approximately $13,200 — a 45% reduction in effective interest cost. This changes the cost-benefit analysis of investment property leverage significantly and should be factored into any cash flow analysis.</p>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Always consult your accountant regarding the tax implications of your rental property financing, particularly around the treatment of interest on refinanced amounts and the interaction with the passive income rules for incorporated landlords.</p>

